                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/CharGenTCPClient.java"

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/DaytimeTCPClient.java"

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/DiscardTCPClient.java"

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ProtocolCommandListener.java"

But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).                     "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/TimeUDPClient.java"

I changed the connection hooks (_connectAction_())\nfor the FTP, SMTP, POP3, and NNTP classes to force use of an 8-bit\nUS-ASCII superset (ISO-8859-1) for protocol communication.  This was\nnecessary because InputStreamReader and OutputStreamWriter use the default\nclient-side character set encoding.  I don't know if this should be\nuser-configurable or if the encodings should be fixed.  Regardless,\nall JVMs are required to support US-ASCII and ISO-8859-1, so there\nshouldn't be a problem with using a fixed encoding.\n\nPR: 22656\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139399 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTP.java"

So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTP.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 15,
                    "commit message": "First swipe at cleanup of code.  Changed spacing/formatting and import\nstatement cleansing.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139295 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTPClient.java"
                },
                {
                    "commit index": 17,
                    "commit message": "Patch/Description provided by Steve Cohen:\n\nThis code implements Daniel's suggested for a Parser implementation that\nis less wasteful of memory since it saves only the original listing and\ncreates more expensive FTPFile instances on an as needed basis only.  It\nsupports paged and single file iteration through the list using iterator-like\nhasNext() - next() syntax.  The next() methods can return either one or\nmany entries.  Iteration is bidirectional.  There are hasPrevious() and\nprevious() methods as well.  It should be possible, using this system to\ncreate attractive, efficient, paged GUI displays of FTP directories.\n\nIt also features a revised version of Daniel's DefaultFTPFileLister that\nuses regular expressions, as well as revised versions of Winston Ojeda's\nVMS, OS2, and NT parsers that make more use of regular expressions and\nin some cases, recover more information than the originals did.  However\nthese implementations were skeletal and they are still not complete.  I think\nthey are also rather old and I would be highly surprised if OS2 and NT\nFTP servers have not been released in a Y2K compliant way in the past couple\nof years.  Someone more experienced with these systems should have a look\nat these parsers and see if they can't be improved.  I'm quite sure they can.\n\nMy design of this subsystem decouples the parsing aspect from the listing\naspect.  A single file ENTRY is parsed, not a LIST of files.\n\nIn order to achieve this design, a new interface, FTPFileEntryParser, has\nbeen created to be used in place of FTPFileListParser.  The listing portion\nis handled by a new FTPFileList class and the iterative aspect has been\nencapsulated in an FTPFileIterator class.\n\nI had a hard time in designing these enhancements, deciding how to lay out\nthe classes.  Support for the new file listing mechanism would require\nmassive changes to FTPClient.  I was very leery of making these because it\nseemed to me that this would add large doses of confusion to the system, and\nmight well lead to it not being accepted by the community.  This is especially\nso at this time, when the community process for NetComponents is very much\nup in the air.\n\nAccordingly I decided to make NO changes to FTPClient, and instead to place the\nnew code in a class DERIVED from FTPClient to keep the two systems separable in\nthe minds of users, which would help the emerging NetComponents community decide\nwhether and how to best incorporate the new ideas.  I almost succeeded in this\ngoal - I did have to make the __openDataConnection() method of FTPClient\nprotected instead of private in order to use it with the new derived class.\n\nIn line with keeping the experimental part of this revision as separate as possible,\nall of my new code except the change to FTPClient is furthermore placed in\na new package com.oroinc.net.ftp.ftp2.  This will probably not be its\nfinal home, but it will do for now, again to help the community evaluate\nthese changes.\n\nAs mentioned above, I have incorporated into this version revised versions\nof Winston Ojeda's replacement parsers, which work with the FTPFileEntryParser.\nThese derive from a helper class that encapsulates the Regular Expression\ncode in one place, making more possible replacement by a different regex\nengine sometime in the future, if desired, although the present one seems\nquite good enough.  I also took the liberty of removing the main() functions\nin Winston's code for testing and included a JUnit testing apparatus that\nis reachable from ant.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139299 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTPClient.java"
                },

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTPFileListParser.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/io/FromNetASCIIOutputStream.java"

                    "commit index": 76,
                    "commit message": "fasselin@ca.ibm.com reported failure of SMTP on OS/390 which has EBCDIC as the\nnative character set.  I changed the connection hooks (_connectAction_())\nfor the FTP, SMTP, POP3, and NNTP classes to force use of an 8-bit\nUS-ASCII superset (ISO-8859-1) for protocol communication.  This was\nnecessary because InputStreamReader and OutputStreamWriter use the default\nclient-side character set encoding.  I don't know if this should be\nuser-configurable or if the encodings should be fixed.  Regardless,\nall JVMs are required to support US-ASCII and ISO-8859-1, so there\nshouldn't be a problem with using a fixed encoding.\n\nPR: 22656\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139399 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/nntp/NNTP.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 76,
                    "commit message": "fasselin@ca.ibm.com reported failure of SMTP on OS/390 which has EBCDIC as the\nnative character set.  I changed the connection hooks (_connectAction_())\nfor the FTP, SMTP, POP3, and NNTP classes to force use of an 8-bit\nUS-ASCII superset (ISO-8859-1) for protocol communication.  This was\nnecessary because InputStreamReader and OutputStreamWriter use the default\nclient-side character set encoding.  I don't know if this should be\nuser-configurable or if the encodings should be fixed.  Regardless,\nall JVMs are required to support US-ASCII and ISO-8859-1, so there\nshouldn't be a problem with using a fixed encoding.\n\nPR: 22656\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139399 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/pop3/POP3.java"

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/pop3/POP3.java"
                },
                {
                    "commit index": 141,
                    "commit message": "Corrected remaining bad javadoc links that pointed to JDK 1.1 javadoc\nhtml files.  For posterity, the following kluge handled the multiline\ncase:\n for i in $(find -name \"*.java\"); do\n  perl -e '@foo = <>; $foo = join(\"\", @foo); $foo =~ s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">(\\s*\\*\\s*)[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}$2/sg; $foo =~ s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">(\\s*\\*\\s*)([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $4}$3/sg; $foo =~ s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">(\\s*\\*\\s*)([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $3}$2/sg; print \"$foo\";' < $i > $i.new\n done\n\nAlso, I noted some ^M characters after a bunch of package names and\nconverted them to newlines.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139516 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/pop3/POP3.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 76,
                    "commit message": "fasselin@ca.ibm.com reported failure of SMTP on OS/390 which has EBCDIC as the\nnative character set.  I changed the connection hooks (_connectAction_())\nfor the FTP, SMTP, POP3, and NNTP classes to force use of an 8-bit\nUS-ASCII superset (ISO-8859-1) for protocol communication.  This was\nnecessary because InputStreamReader and OutputStreamWriter use the default\nclient-side character set encoding.  I don't know if this should be\nuser-configurable or if the encodings should be fixed.  Regardless,\nall JVMs are required to support US-ASCII and ISO-8859-1, so there\nshouldn't be a problem with using a fixed encoding.\n\nPR: 22656\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139399 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/smtp/SMTP.java"

But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/smtp/SMTP.java"

But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/smtp/SMTPCommand.java"

The method was added\n>in JDK 1.4.\n>\n>2) Empty subjects are in the message.  Now the subject will only be\n>includes when it is non-null.\n\nWhat appears to have happened is that the code relied on an implicit\ntoString() call by the compiler, but after J2SE 1.4 added\nStringBuffer.append(StringBuffer) and the code was compiled using\nJ2SE 1.4 javac, a call to StringBuffer.append(StringBuffer) was\nresolved instead of StringBuffer.append(String).                     "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/telnet/TelnetClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 103,
                    "commit message": "\"Jeff Barrett\" <JBarrett@sawyermedia.com> reports that:\nI'm using commons-net to ftp a bunch of files around every night as a batch process.  It probably copies just under 1g.  Over the course of that process I'll  often get 2 or 3 thrown exceptions like so:\n\n    [java] java.lang.NullPointerException\n    [java] \tat java.io.BufferedInputStream.read(BufferedInputStream.java:279)\n    [java] \tat java.io.BufferedInputStream.fill(BufferedInputStream.java:183)\n    [java] \tat java.io.BufferedInputStream.read(BufferedInputStream.java:201)\n    [java] \tat org.apache.commons.net.telnet.TelnetInputStream.__read(TelnetInputStream.java:140)\n    [java] \tat org.apache.commons.net.telnet.TelnetInputStream.run(TelnetInputStream.java:464)\n    [java] \tat java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:536)\n\nSince we didn't open a Bugzilla report, I'm recording my email\nexplanation as a log message:\n\nThat's all happening in BufferedInputStream.  Looking at the code\nfor BufferedInputStream in J2SE 1.4.2, it looks like the\nNullPointerException exception is happening at a call of in.available().\nin is set to null in close().  So it seems there may be a situation\nwhereby a read by TelnetInputStream.__read is being performed after\na close.  Looking at the code, I'm pretty sure there's a problem.\nTelnetInputStream calls super.close() BEFORE entering a\nsynchronized block.  There's a race condition that could allow\nthe reader thread to start a read after BufferedInputStream.close()\nis called.  The reason it hardly ever happns is that\nBufferedInputStream calls an ensureOpen() method at the\nbeginning of read() that checks to make sure in is not null.\nHowever, between that call and the call to in.available(),\nthe value may become null because BufferdInputStream.close()\nis not a synchronized method, unlike BufferedInputStream.read().\n\nNow, there's a comment in the code before the close\ncall that I'm guilty of that says:\n        // Completely disregard the fact thread may still be running.\n        // We can't afford to block on this close by waiting for\n        // thread to terminate because few if any JVM's will actually\n        // interrupt a system read() from the interrupt() method.\nThis means the close() is being used to force the read() to return -1\nor throw an exception.  If we synchronize the call to close, we\nmay get deadlock.  Mind you, this is circa JDK 1.1.x.\n\nThe good news is that the NullPointerException is probably harmless\nbecause it's happening when the stream is being closed and the thread\nis terminated.  Also, it's the FTP control stream, not the data stream\nthat's being affected, so there will be no loss of data.  The bad\nnews is that I'm not immediately sure how to fix it in light of the\ncode comment.  This is a great example of why I'd like to get rid of\nthe threads and move to java.nio for version 2.0.\n\nI can't come up with any ideas that don't run the risk of\ndeadlock on some JVM.  I'm afraid the right fix may be to\nsimply catch any RuntimeExceptions thrown by read and take\nthe same action as a close().  We probably should have been\ndoing that anyway to gracefully handle unexpected situations.\nAs an interim fix, I applied that change.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139442 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/telnet/TelnetInputStream.java"
                },

But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/tftp/TFTP.java"

So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/tftp/TFTPClient.java"

So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/tftp/TFTPErrorPacket.java"
                },

For posterity, the following kluge handled the multiline\ncase:\n for i in $(find -name \"*.java\"); do\n  perl -e '@foo = <>; $foo = join(\"\", @foo); $foo =~ s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">(\\s*\\*\\s*)[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}$2/sg; $foo =~ s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">(\\s*\\*\\s*)([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $4}$3/sg; $foo =~ s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">(\\s*\\*\\s*)([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $3}$2/sg; print \"$foo\";' < $i > $i.new\n done\n\nAlso, I noted some ^M characters after a bunch of package names and\nconverted them to newlines.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139516 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/tftp/TFTPErrorPacket.java"

But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/tftp/TFTPRequestPacket.java"

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 proposal/ftp2/src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/ftp2/FTPFileEntryParser.java"

                    "commit index": 140,
                    "commit message": "What I tried to do was replace the references to straight up files\nwith\n{@link classname} or {@link classname#member} and references to in\nfile anchors with {@link #member}.  But there were quite a number of\nclassname.html#_top_ references and I replaced those with {@link\nclassname}.\nSo I ended up running the following:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e\n 's/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(?:#_top_)?\">[^<]+<\\/a>/{\\@link $1}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"([^\"]+)\\.html(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1$2 $3}/g;\n s/<a\\s+href=\"(#[^\"]+)\">([^<]+)<\\/a>/{\\@link $1 $2}/g'\n\nI doublechecked that everything still compiled fine and that 'maven\njavadoc'\ndidn't choke.  javadoc spouted warnings because there were typos in\nthe\nsome of the links (e.g., sendComand instead of sendCommand).  So I fixed\nthose with:\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/Comand/Command/g'\n find -name \"*.java\" | xargs perl -pi -e 's/recieve/receive/g'\nThere were some mistaken references to sendMessage which should have\nbeen\nsendMessageData in SMTPClient, so I fixed those similarly.\n\nLastly, FTPClient had a reference to Package-packagename.html which were\ntranslated into @link Package-packagename, so I trimmed off the Package-,\nleaving {@link org.apache.commons.net.io}, which javadoc complained\nabout with:\n  warning - Tag @link: reference not found: org.apache.commons.net.io\nThis is supposed to work, so I left it alone because the only damage\ndone\nto the docs is that the package name is printed without a hyperlink.\n\nThere are still a bunch of .html links that span across two javadoc\nlines and I'll fix those next, but wanted to report on the initial fixes and\ncheck them in.\n\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/jakarta/commons/proper/net/trunk@139515 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTPFileEntryParser.java"

                },
                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/DatagramSocketClient.java"
                },
                {
                    "commit index": 1102,
                    "commit message": "Restore Java 1.5 compatibility\nAll code changes are marked with Java 1.6 so can easily be found later\n@Overrides are commented out rather than removed (easier to do global replace)\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1489361 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/DatagramSocketClient.java"
                },

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/SocketClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/bsd/RExecClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/pop3/POP3Client.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTPListParseEngine.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/daytime/DaytimeTCPClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/finger/FingerClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/telnet/Telnet.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/ftp/FTPHTTPClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/pop3/ExtendedPOP3Client.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/smtp/AuthenticatingSMTPClient.java"

                {
                    "commit index": 1071,
                    "commit message": "Add a Charset field to the two root abstract socket classes that provide a common base implementation for socket-based subclasses. The default value is the platform encoding. Subclasses can now use this value instead of relying on APIs that do not specify an encoding. For example String#getBytes(Charset) instead of getBytes(). The behavior is unchanged but the FindBugs emits fewer warnings. Note that it is now easy for subclasses to specify an encoding consistently. If you search for \"UTF-8\", you find uses of the \"UTF-8\" encoding and of the platform encoding in the same class, which are likely bugs. These can now be fixed in a much easier and consistent manner.\n\ngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/commons/proper/net/trunk@1414510 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68 src/main/java/org/apache/commons/net/imap/AuthenticatingIMAPClient.java"
